al approach remains attractive to many Islamists. Addressing these issues, the contributors look at the countries where Islamist movements have been most important. Case studies of revolutionary and reformist groups are followed by chapters discussing future alternatives for Islamist politics, presenting arguments both advocating and critical of a potential liberal, reformist, interest-group Islamism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aIslam and politicsxMiddle East. 0aIslam and politicszMiddle East. 0aIslam and statexMiddle East. 0aIslam and statezMiddle East. 0aIslam et politiquexMoyen-Orient. 0aIslam et ÉtatxMoyen-Orient. 0aIslamx20th centuryxMiddle East. 0aIslamxHistoirex20e sièclexMoyen-Orient. 0aIslamzMiddle Easty20th century. 0aIslamic renewalxMiddle East. 0aIslamic renewalzMiddle East. 0aRenouveau islamiquexMoyen-Orient. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Islam. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh1 aAbootalebi, Ali R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAras, Bulent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaha, Omer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEickelman, Dale F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhabra, Shafeeq N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrani, George E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarmon, Ely, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurzman, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLitvak, Meir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaddy-Weitzman, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarli, Nilufer, econtributo